45.2.2 Managing input for wastegate actuator
� General Information
This function calculates the wastegate setpoint from EOL side towards charger aggregate. Like this EOL pro-
duces 1 interface from the actuator test and short trip variables.
� Application Conditions
Initialisation: At reset, ECU state OFF to ON:
For i = 0 to NC_NR_BPA - 1
POSN_SP_BPA_EXT[i] = 0
LV_BPA_EXT_REQ[i] = 0
Endfor
LV_TMP_REQ = 0
Activation: always
Deactivation: never
Recurrence: 10ms
� Function Description
For i = 0 to NC_NR_BPA - 1
If LV_BPA_EXT_REQ_ACT[i] == 1
Then
LV_BPA_EXT_REQ[i] = LV_BPA_EXT_REQ_ACT[i]
POSN_SP_BPA_EXT[i] = POSN_SP_BPA_EXT_ACT[i]
Elseif LV_BPA_TEST_2_EXT_REQ == 1
Then
LV_BPA_EXT_REQ[i] = LV_BPA_EXT_REQ_EOL
POSN_SP_BPA_EXT[i] = POSN_SP_BPA_EXT_EOL
Else
LV_BPA_EXT_REQ[i] = 0
POSN_SP_BPA_EXT[i] = 0
Endif
Endfor

GEOL, Quick sleep current measurement (Appl. Inc.)
After x seconds (e.g. 60s) an automatic measurement will start at the end of the production line. At this time
the ECU must be in sleeping mode (of?ine), because the standby current will be measured. To guarantee that
the ECU is sleeping at that time, needed power lock conditions (PWL) will be stored into EEPROM. If there a
PWL-condition is set to 1, the ECU was not sleeping during the measurement, then the measured values are
illegal.
/* At this project T_PWL has the resolution 0,1 and unit [s]. T_PWL_S has the resolution 1 and unit [s].
Therefore an adaptation is necessary: */
T_PWL_S = T_PWL / 10;
If the project does not support the following powerlatch lock conditions, the affected bits must be set to "0".
45.4.1 Function 1
� General Information
� Application Conditions
Initialisation: at reset:
LV_CUR_MES_STB_MOD_ENA = 0
Activation: LV_ES = 1 (1 = Engine Stopped)
LV_PWL_ACT = 0
Deactivation: LV_ES = 0
LV_PWL_ACT = 1
Recurrence: 100ms
� Function Description
IF(1) (LV_MES_MOD_ACT and LV_SYS_INFO_CAN_VLD)
ACTION_FARM_GetPermission(IN<NC_FID_CUR_MES_SYS_INFO_OK>))
THEN(1)
/* set measurement request */
LV_CUR_MES_STB_MOD_ENA = 1;
ELSE(1)
/* reset measurement request because of CAN communication problem or request
is canceled*/
LV_CUR_MES_STB_MOD_ENA = 0;
ENDIF(1)
Remark: NC_FID_CUR_MES_SYS_INFO_OK to be configured to MASK AERR of AUX_CAN_
SYSINFO_1_TOUT or AUX_CAN_SYSINFO_1_PLAUS or NC_IDX_FID_ERR_COM_0_TOT or NC_
IDX_FID_ERR_COM_0_BOFF

The variable STATE_FCT_INTR_EOL records the reason why the EOL procedure has been interrupted. This
variable will be evaluated within the EOL communication interface module and via UDS Service 22 ID 0x108
"Cause of routine termination" the reason of the interruption will be displayed in the garage tester.

45.7.3.1.1 FCTM_MANGEOL0/CLC_OPERATE/TEST_MODE_ACTIVE/TEST_REQUIREMENT
Autonomous EOL mode (devoid of constant driver activity) is discerned per security access from manual EOL
mode (with constant driver activity). When autonomous mode: after activation of security access will wait
on a valid short trip request inside 60 second. If it is not timely happened, then will be immediately broken
the autonomous EOL mode. After the timely derivation the EOL enabling conditions will be checked. When
manual EOL mode the EOL enabling conditions will be immediately checked.

45.7.3.1.2 FCTM_MANGEOL0/CLC_OPERATE/TEST_MODE_ACTIVE/TEST_PROCEDURE
In this subsystem will issue the activated short trip and his status. When controlled progression of short trips
(MVB 200,201 and 202) will the maximum remaining runtime of selected test and number of tests in the
activation waiting loop. The collecting test can be rerun only after reset of error memory. In case of Single test
at LV_ACT_EOL rising edge the T_EOL is initialized according to the MAP ID_T_EOL(MVB_EOL). When the single
test is performed and LV_END_DIAG is set, in the module ACTIVATION OF THE WAIT MODE
"LV_ACT_EOL" will be set to zero. Because in this module LV_END_DIAG is in input with a delay but
LV_ACT_EOL is not delayed, the decrement of CTR_EOL will be not performed because LV_ACT_EOL will have
effect one step before.
In case a Diesel automated EOL procedure is executed the LV_ERR_DIAG is set only at the end of the EOL pro-
cedure if an error has been recognized during the test. for Gasoline con?guration LV_ERR_DIAG is immediately
set.

45.7.3.1.3.2 FCTM_MANGEOL0/CLC_OPERATE/TEST_MODE_ACTIVE/CALCULATIONS/ECF_ACC_REQ
During EOL procedure it is possible to activate the air condition via LV_ACC_ACT_EOL_REQ = 1. In autonomous
mode the ID_MVB_EOL_ACC_REQ[MVB_EOL].bit1 is activating this request and in manual mode ID_MVB_EOL_
ACC_REQ[MVB_EOL].bit3.
Via the request PWM_ECF_EOL_REQ_SNG_1 a cooling fan setpoint can be applied during EOL test individually
for each MVB_EOL.

45.7.3.1.4 FCTM_MANGEOL0/CLC_OPERATE/TEST_MODE_ACTIVE/RELEASE_PROCEDURE
The EOL enabling procedure comprise from checking of the EOL enabling conditions and deactivation of
waiting mode for bath EOL modes. Out of safety reason when autonomous EOL mode has an activation pro-
cedure (pedal check) extra and the realization of the EOL enabling procedure is time-limited. The EOL enabling
procedure must be executed effective inside 60 second. If it is not timely happened, then will be immediately
broken the autonomous EOL mode. This mode can be again activated by a new security access.
When inspection of the EOL enabling conditions will be checked ?rst the joint conditions and following the
EOL mode speci?c conditions. If after a realization of the EOL enabling procedure one of the conditions will
be disabled, a break of the selected test will be effected. The healing of condition break (per new short trip
request) and the new activity of the EOL enabling procedure in autonomous EOL mode must be executed
effective inside 60 second. If it is not timely happened, then will be immediately broken the autonomous EOL
mode. This mode can be again activated by a new security access.

If the EOL enabling conditions are ful?lled, will checked the next conditions. If this conditions are not satisfy, will
activated the waiting made. If these conditions are satis?ed, in manual EOL mode will activated the selected
test and in autonomous EOL mode can started the vital pedal check. The transition in the waiting mode with
a running test will lead to the test break.
If after activation of waiting mode in autonomous EOL mode the EOL enabling procedure wills not effective
executed inside 60 second, then will be immediately broken the autonomous EOL mode. This mode can be
again activated by a new security access.
When pedal check will reviewed the activity of the pedals (the brake, the clutch (not when automatic) and the
accelerator).

Else(1)

STATE_FCT_INTR_EOL_COM = N_MAX_OVER_STEP //Condition J) or E)
Else(2)
If(3) ((LV_DIAG_SES_UDS_EOL_ACT = 1 And

TAM_EOL >C_TAM_GEOL_ASA_MAX Or
TEG_DYN_DOWN_CAT >C_TEG_GEOL_ASA_MAX )))
Then(3) PRM_NR_RESP_COD = 0x86 // temperature too high
STATE_FCT_INTR_EOL_COM = INH_TEMP // Condition L)

This image displays a Stateflow diagram, which is a component within the Simulink environment. It models the operational states and transitions for an automotive actuator test.

## Function

The primary function of this Simulink diagram is to manage the lifecycle of an Actuator Test (likely an Air Conditioning Actuator Test, based on "ACR" in `STATE_TST_ACR`). It defines the conditions under which the test starts, runs actively, gets cancelled due to deviations, ends due to timeout, or is explicitly stopped, ensuring robust control and error handling within an Electronic Control Unit (ECU).

## Inputs

The key inputs that trigger state transitions and influence the logic flow are:

*   **`At ECU reset`**: A system-level event indicating the ECU has been reset.
*   **`ACTION_FCMT_StartAcrTst`**: A command signal from a diagnostic tester to initiate the actuator test.
*   **`ACTION_FCMT_StopAcrTst`**: A command signal from a diagnostic tester to terminate the actuator test.
*   **`Aktivierungsbedingungen` (Activation Conditions)**: A set of six boolean conditions that must all be TRUE (`&&` operator) for the test to start:
    *   `LV_IGK = 1`
    *   `LV_ES = 1`
    *   `VS = 0`
    *   `LV_ACR_TST_DI = 0`
    *   `LV_FFFF_ACT = 0`
    *   `LV_STST_STOP_CYC = 0`
*   **`Abweichende Aktivierungs Bedingungen sind:` (Deviant Activation Conditions)**: A set of six boolean conditions, where if any one is TRUE (`OR` operator), the test is cancelled. These represent conditions that make the test unsafe or invalid:
    *   `LV_IGK = 0`
    *   `LV_ES = 0`
    *   `VS > 0`
    *   `LV_ACR_TST_DI = 1`
    *   `LV_FFFF_ACT = 1`
    *   `LV_STST_STOP_CYC = 1`
*   **`Test länger als vorgegeben Zeit (60s)`**: A timeout condition, indicating that the test has exceeded a predefined duration of 60 seconds.

## Outputs

The primary output of this system is the `STATE_TST_ACR` variable, which represents the current state of the actuator test. This state is also mapped to a `SOC` (Status of Controller) value:

*   **`STATE_TST_ACR = NC_STATE_ACR_TST_DEF` (SOC=0x00)**: The default/inactive state. Indicates all actuators are under the control of the normal driving program.
*   **`STATE_TST_ACR = NC_STATE_ACR_TST_ACT` (SOC=0xC0)**: The active state. Indicates that a selected test is currently running.
*   **`STATE_TST_ACR = NC_STATE_ACR_TST_CNL` (SOC=0x40)**: The cancelled state. Indicates the test was aborted by the controller due to security or operational criteria.
*   **`STATE_TST_ACR = NC_STATE_ACR_TST_END` (SOC=0x80)**: The ended state. Indicates the test concluded because it exceeded its allocated time.

## Logic Flow

The logical flow of the actuator test state machine is as follows:

1.  **Initialization (`NC_STATE_ACR_TST_DEF`, SOC=0x00):**
    *   Upon an **ECU reset**, the system enters the `NC_STATE_ACR_TST_DEF` state. In this state, the actuator test is not active, and the actuators are controlled by the regular driving program.

2.  **Starting the Test (`NC_STATE_ACR_TST_ACT`, SOC=0xC0):**
    *   From the `NC_STATE_ACR_TST_DEF` state, if a `ACTION_FCMT_StartAcrTst` command is received from a tester **AND** all "Aktivierungsbedingungen" (Activation Conditions) are met, the system transitions to the `NC_STATE_ACR_TST_ACT` state. The test is now active.

3.  **Active Test Phase:**

## Logic Flow

The Stateflow chart operates with a top-level `active` state and an `inactiv` state, and within the `active` state, it manages parallel checks for the "Brake" (including clutch) and "Accelerator" pedals.

1.  **Initial State (`inactiv`):**
    *   The system typically starts in the `inactiv` state.
    *   **Transition to `active`**: The system transitions to the `active` state if `PV_AV_H` is low (e.g., accelerator released) AND `ILV_WAIT_EXT_REQ` is false, OR if various `LV_CLU_SWI` conditions are met. This initiates the pedal check procedure.

2.  **Active State (`active`):**
    *   Upon entering `active`, two parallel processes begin:
        *   **Brake/Clutch Pedal Check (`Brake` and `Brake_active` super-states):**
            *   **`Brake` (Main Sequence):**
                *   **`Start`**: The initial state, where `LV_BRAKE_CLU_ACT_EOL` is set to `1` (Brake/Clutch EOL test active).
                *   **`Bremspedal betätigen` (Brake pedal actuated)**: Transitions from `Start` if `LV_AT` (pedal actuated) is true. `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` is set to `5`.
                *   **`Warten auf Bremse und Kupplung` (Waiting for Brake and Clutch)**: Transitions from `Bremspedal betätigen` if complex conditions involving `ILV_PV_AV_H`, `LV_WAIT_EXT_REQ`, and `ILV_INH_DRI_AUT_MOD_EOL_in` are met. In this state, `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` is set to `3`. It checks multiple `LV_CLU_SWI`, `LC_INH_CLU_SWI`, `LV_BTS`, `LV_BLS`, `LV_BRAKE_EOL` and `LV_CLU_EOL` signals to ensure pedals are in the correct "waiting" state. `LV_BRAKE_EOL` and `LV_CLU_EOL` are set to `0` or `1` based on specific conditions in transition actions.
                *   **`Kupplung und Bremse betätigt` (Clutch and Brake actuated)**: Transitions from `Warten auf Bremse und Kupplung` if `LV_CLU_SWI_1` and `LV_BRAKE_EOL` are true, and other switch conditions (`LV_BTS`, `LV_BLS`, `LV_CLU_SWI_2`, `LC_INH_CLU_SWI_2`) are met. `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` is set to `1`. This state also transitions if the brake pedal alone is actuated and `LV_CLU_SWI` is active.
                    *   It can transition back to `Warten auf Bremse und Kupplung` if `LV_CLU_EOL` or `LV_BRAKE_EOL` conditions change.
            *   **`Brake_active` (Release Sequence, parallel to `Brake`'s main sequence):**
                *   **`Bremspedal lösen` (Brake pedal released)**: Sets `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` to `6`. Transitions based on `LV_AT`.
                *   **`Bremspedal und Kupplungspedal lösen` (Brake and Clutch pedal released)**: Sets `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` to `4`. Transitions based on `LV_BTS`, `LV_BLS`, `LV_CLU_SWI` and `LC_INH_CLU_SWI` conditions.

        *   **Accelerator Pedal Check (`Accelerator` super-state):**
            *   **`Start`**: The initial state, where `LV_BRAKE_CLU_ACT_EOL` is set to `1`.
            *   **`Gaspedal durchtreten` (Accelerator pedal fully pressed)**: Sets `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` to `7`. Transitions if engine speed (`N_32`) exceeds `C_N_MIN_VST_EOL` AND accelerator position (`PV_AV_H`) is above `C_PV_AV_MIN_EXT_REQ`.
            *   **`Accelerator active/entry`**: An intermediate state or entry action that sets `LV_IS_EOL = 1`.

*   **`Gaspedal durchtreten` (Accelerator pedal fully pressed)**: Sets `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` to `7`. Transitions if engine speed (`N_32`) exceeds `C_N_MIN_VST_EOL` AND accelerator position (`PV_AV_H`) is above `C_PV_AV_MIN_EXT_REQ`.
            *   **`Accelerator active/entry`**: An intermediate state or entry action that sets `LV_IS_EOL = 1`.
            *   **`Text aktiv` (Test active)**: This state's entry actions set multiple variables: `LV_INH_DRI_AUT_MOD_EOL = 1`, `LV_BRAKE_EOL = 0`, `LV_BRAKE_CLU_ACT_EOL = 0`, `LV_CLU_EOL = 0`, `LV_CDN_ACT_EOL_INH_DRIV = 0`. `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` is set to `9`. This state likely signifies an active measurement or final configuration within the accelerator test.
            *   **`Gaspedal lösen` (Accelerator pedal released)**: Sets `STATE_DISP_OUT_EOL` to `8`. Transitions if `PV_AV_H` is `0` (pedal fully released).
            *   **`END`**: The final state for the accelerator check, setting `LV_ACT_EOL_MEM = 1`. This marks the completion of the accelerator pedal test.

3.  **Deactivation:**
    *   **Transition from `active` to `inactiv`**: The entire pedal check process can be terminated by transitioning from the `active` state to `inactiv` if `STATE_SHO_TRIP_COM` is `1`. In this transition, several flags related to EOL, drive inhibit, brake, and clutch status are reset to `0`.

## Function

The primary function of this Simulink diagram is to calculate and maintain a "Tip-In synchro flag" (specifically, `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_SYN`) based on the detection of rising edges of two distinct input signals. This flag likely indicates a synchronization event related to an engine speed setpoint at the End Of Line (EOL) phase, triggered by a "Tip-In" condition and potentially cleared by a hold condition.

## Inputs

1.  **`LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP`**: This signal serves as the "Set" trigger for the synchro flag. It is processed by a "Rising edge1" block, meaning only an upward transition (from 0 to 1) of this signal will have an effect.
2.  **`LV_T_HLD_N_SP_IS_EOL`**: This signal serves as the "Reset" trigger for the synchro flag. It is processed by a "Rising edge2" block, meaning only an upward transition (from 0 to 1) of this signal will have an effect.

## Outputs

1.  **`LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_SYN`**: This is the main output, representing the "Tip-In synchro flag." Its value (0 or 1) is determined by the state of the internal S-R Flip-Flop. The label "GEOL: Engine speed setpoint for EOL" provides context for this flag's usage.
2.  The inverted output (`!Q`) of the S-R Flip-Flop is connected to a `Terminator4` block, indicating it is not used as an output from this specific subsystem.

## Logic Flow

The diagram implements a simple Set-Reset (S-R) Flip-Flop logic, triggered by rising edges of its inputs:

1.  **Edge Detection for Set**: The input signal `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP` is fed into a "Rising edge1" block. This block outputs a momentary pulse (typically a 1 for one sample time) whenever `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP` transitions from a low state (0) to a high state (1).

**Edge Detection for Set**: The input signal `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP` is fed into a "Rising edge1" block. This block outputs a momentary pulse (typically a 1 for one sample time) whenever `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP` transitions from a low state (0) to a high state (1). The output of this block directly connects to the 'S' (Set) input of the S-R Flip-Flop.
2.  **Edge Detection for Reset**: Similarly, the input signal `LV_T_HLD_N_SP_IS_EOL` is fed into a "Rising edge2" block. This block outputs a momentary pulse whenever `LV_T_HLD_N_SP_IS_EOL` transitions from a low state (0) to a high state (1). The output of this block directly connects to the 'R' (Reset) input of the S-R Flip-Flop.
3.  **S-R Flip-Flop Operation**:
    *   When a rising edge is detected on `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP` (asserting 'S'), and no rising edge is simultaneously detected on `LV_T_HLD_N_SP_IS_EOL` (R is not asserted), the 'Q' output of the S-R Flip-Flop is set to 1.
    *   When a rising edge is detected on `LV_T_HLD_N_SP_IS_EOL` (asserting 'R'), and no rising edge is simultaneously detected on `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_FLOP` (S is not asserted), the 'Q' output of the S-R Flip-Flop is reset to 0.
    *   If neither 'S' nor 'R' is asserted (no rising edges on either input), the 'Q' output retains its previous state.
    *   (Typically, if both S and R are asserted simultaneously, the behavior is implementation-dependent; often, R takes precedence, or the state becomes indeterminate, though designs usually avoid this condition).
4.  **Output**: The 'Q' output of the S-R Flip-Flop is directly passed as the `LV_N_SP_IS_EOL_TIPIN_SYN` signal, serving as the calculated Tip-In synchro flag. This flag remains set to 1 until a reset condition is met.
